They just need to look
it up and find out

00:28:16.900 --> 00:28:18.460 align:middle line:84%
where it's showing
around their area, right?

00:28:18.460 --> 00:28:18.850 align:middle line:90%
>>ALVARADO: That's correct.

00:28:18.850 --> 00:28:21.130 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's not on DVD release
or anything at this point?

00:28:21.130 --> 00:28:21.963 align:middle line:90%
>>ALVARADO: Not yet.

00:28:21.963 --> 00:28:24.220 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Other than Gaiam
TV, which is fantastic.

00:28:24.220 --> 00:28:24.720 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:28:24.720 --> 00:28:27.440 align:middle line:84%
So there's another whole
opposing perspective

00:28:27.440 --> 00:28:31.490 align:middle line:84%
that's presented in the
film in Aubrey's hometown.

00:28:31.490 --> 00:28:34.730 align:middle line:84%
And he is brought in front
of a review board there.

00:28:34.730 --> 00:28:38.294 align:middle line:84%
Did that come up by chance
when you were filming?

00:28:38.294 --> 00:28:38.960 align:middle line:90%
>>SUSSBERG: Mhm.

00:28:38.960 --> 00:28:39.460 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:28:39.460 --> 00:28:41.897 align:middle line:84%
So it's actually
Oxford, England,

00:28:41.897 --> 00:28:43.480 align:middle line:84%
and actually, Aubrey's
from Cambridge.

00:28:43.480 --> 00:28:46.860 align:middle line:90%
And so he's invited to a debate.

00:28:46.860 --> 00:28:52.180 align:middle line:84%
And they had a long legacy of
doing these scientific debates

00:28:52.180 --> 00:28:53.010 align:middle line:90%
at Oxford.

00:28:53.010 --> 00:28:55.422 align:middle line:84%
And so on the one
hand, we have Aubrey

00:28:55.422 --> 00:28:57.380 align:middle line:84%
saying that we should
live as long as possible,

00:28:57.380 --> 00:28:59.330 align:middle line:84%
and we should do
everything to defeat aging.

00:28:59.330 --> 00:29:01.750 align:middle line:84%
On the other hand, there's
Dr. Colin Blakemore

00:29:01.750 --> 00:29:06.430 align:middle line:84%
who says that it's neither
desirable nor is it feasible.

00:29:06.430 --> 00:29:08.790 align:middle line:84%
And we did not
actually set that up.

00:29:08.790 --> 00:29:11.130 align:middle line:90%
That was happening organically.

00:29:11.130 --> 00:29:15.370 align:middle line:84%
And it allowed us to get into
the ethical, thornier issues,

00:29:15.370 --> 00:29:19.070 align:middle line:84%
and to let other sides present
their case that what Aubrey was

00:29:19.070 --> 00:29:24.060 align:middle line:84%
saying was not desirable
and was misguided.

00:29:24.060 --> 00:29:26.160 align:middle line:84%
We actually learned about
that about three days

00:29:26.160 --> 00:29:27.476 align:middle line:90%
before it happened.

00:29:27.476 --> 00:29:29.725 align:middle line:84%
Aubrey let us know that,
hey, this debate's happening.

00:29:29.725 --> 00:29:31.696 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That's
gold for you guys.

00:29:31.696 --> 00:29:32.564 align:middle line:90%
>>SUSSBERG: Yeah.

00:29:32.564 --> 00:29:33.980 align:middle line:84%
This might be great
for your film.

00:29:33.980 --> 00:29:37.800 align:middle line:84%
And at the time, we immediately
started producing it,

00:29:37.800 --> 00:29:40.330 align:middle line:84%
and we turned it
around really quick.

00:29:40.330 --> 00:29:42.720 align:middle line:84%
But that was
happening organically.

00:29:42.720 --> 00:29:45.520 align:middle line:84%
And we always wanted things
to happen in the film

00:29:45.520 --> 00:29:46.770 align:middle line:90%
as they happened in real life.

00:29:46.770 --> 00:29:49.205 align:middle line:84%
We really kept a
gentle touch on it.

00:29:49.205 --> 00:29:50.830 align:middle line:84%
We didn't really want
to force anything

00:29:50.830 --> 00:29:52.995 align:middle line:84%
to actually happen
other than what

00:29:52.995 --> 00:29:54.120 align:middle line:90%
was happening in real life.

00:29:54.120 --> 00:29:55.560 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I love the
timing of this.

00:29:55.560 --> 00:29:57.518 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to have you
take a look at this clip.

00:29:57.518 --> 00:30:00.340 align:middle line:84%
And just pay attention to
the timing, and the music,

00:30:00.340 --> 00:30:02.820 align:middle line:84%
and the contemplation
that you allow

00:30:02.820 --> 00:30:05.270 align:middle line:84%
the audience to have
within this debate.

00:30:05.270 --> 00:30:06.020 align:middle line:90%
It's really great.

00:30:06.020 --> 00:30:06.990 align:middle line:90%
It's very well done.

00:30:06.990 --> 00:30:07.490 align:middle line:90%
Take a look.

00:30:07.490 --> 00:30:14.200 align:middle line:90%


00:30:14.200 --> 00:30:18.690 align:middle line:84%
>>ANDREWS: 85% to 95% of all
cancers produce telomerase.

00:30:18.690 --> 00:30:21.190 align:middle line:84%
That has led a lot
of people to believe

00:30:21.190 --> 00:30:24.880 align:middle line:84%
that telomerase is
the cause of cancer.

00:30:24.880 --> 00:30:26.487 align:middle line:90%
But it's not.

00:30:26.487 --> 00:30:28.195 align:middle line:84%
The most direct thing
that causes cancers

00:30:28.195 --> 00:30:30.110 align:middle line:90%
is the mutations.

00:30:30.110 --> 00:30:33.540 align:middle line:84%
So the key is to prevent these
mutations from occurring.

00:30:33.540 --> 00:30:37.350 align:middle line:84%
But one of the biggest
causes of these mutations

00:30:37.350 --> 00:30:38.525 align:middle line:90%
is short telomeres.

00:30:38.525 --> 00:30:42.900 align:middle line:90%


00:30:42.900 --> 00:30:44.900 align:middle line:84%
>>DE GREY: Telomerase
in human beings

00:30:44.900 --> 00:30:48.410 align:middle line:84%
is expressed at very low
levels, only just enough

00:30:48.410 --> 00:30:51.620 align:middle line:84%
to allow cells to get
along for a lifetime.

00:30:51.620 --> 00:30:54.580 align:middle line:84%
But cancers express high levels
of telomerase most of the time.

00:30:54.580 --> 00:30:56.654 align:middle line:84%
About 90% of cancers
express really high levels.

00:30:56.654 --> 00:30:57.820 align:middle line:90%
>>ANDREWS: Now look at this.

00:30:57.820 --> 00:31:00.177 align:middle line:90%
A low level of oxidative stress.

00:31:00.177 --> 00:31:00.760 align:middle line:90%
>>DE GREY: OK.

00:31:00.760 --> 00:31:01.759 align:middle line:90%
And what was mine again?

00:31:01.759 --> 00:31:03.130 align:middle line:90%
>>WOMAN: 232, I believe it was.

00:31:03.130 --> 00:31:04.380 align:middle line:90%
>>DE GREY: Better than normal.

00:31:04.380 --> 00:31:05.820 align:middle line:90%
>>ANDREWS: Wow.

00:31:05.820 --> 00:31:07.340 align:middle line:90%
I'm getting slaughtered here.

00:31:07.340 --> 00:31:08.240 align:middle line:84%
>>DE GREY: You're just
doing too much running.

00:31:08.240 --> 00:31:09.114 align:middle line:90%
That's what it is.

00:31:09.114 --> 00:31:10.530 align:middle line:84%
>>ANDREWS: What
Aubrey wants to do

00:31:10.530 --> 00:31:13.610 align:middle line:84%
is destroy the telomerase
gene in all of our cells

00:31:13.610 --> 00:31:15.230 align:middle line:90%
in our body.

00:31:15.230 --> 00:31:20.050 align:middle line:84%
And that would then decrease
our chances of getting cancer.

00:31:20.050 --> 00:31:21.850 align:middle line:84%
>>DE GREY: My approach
is to actually use

00:31:21.850 --> 00:31:26.662 align:middle line:84%
telomere shortening as
an anticancer mechanism.

00:31:26.662 --> 00:31:27.370 align:middle line:90%
It's called WILT.

00:31:27.370 --> 00:31:29.050 align:middle line:84%
That stands for
Whole-Body Interdiction

00:31:29.050 --> 00:31:31.820 align:middle line:84%
of Lengthening of Telomeres,
if you really want to know.

00:31:31.820 --> 00:31:34.440 align:middle line:84%
>>ANDREWS: I conceded
that Aubrey beat me

00:31:34.440 --> 00:31:35.840 align:middle line:90%
on the age scan test.

00:31:35.840 --> 00:31:37.620 align:middle line:84%
But then I said to
him, but let's see

00:31:37.620 --> 00:31:40.880 align:middle line:84%
you do as well as I did
when you're 60 years old.

00:31:40.880 --> 00:31:44.177 align:middle line:84%
And he just looks at me and
says, I'm going to do better.

00:31:44.177 --> 00:31:46.510 align:middle line:84%
>>DE GREY: I notice I'm just
getting a lot of reflection

00:31:46.510 --> 00:31:46.970 align:middle line:90%
off the ceiling light.

00:31:46.970 --> 00:31:47.570 align:middle line:90%
I don't know.

00:31:47.570 --> 00:31:48.840 align:middle line:90%
It's just hard to see on this.

00:31:48.840 --> 00:31:50.920 align:middle line:90%
F, D, L, O, P, Z, D. OK.

00:31:50.920 --> 00:31:52.750 align:middle line:84%
And the next one--
oh, god almighty.

00:31:52.750 --> 00:31:55.730 align:middle line:90%


00:31:55.730 --> 00:31:59.640 align:middle line:84%
>>ANDREWS: So really, telomerase
does not cause cancer.

00:31:59.640 --> 00:32:01.690 align:middle line:90%
Cancer causes telomerase.

00:32:01.690 --> 00:32:04.540 align:middle line:84%
But if telomerase
makes a cell healthier,

00:32:04.540 --> 00:32:08.059 align:middle line:84%
it's going to make a
cancer cell healthier too.

00:32:08.059 --> 00:32:09.008 align:middle line:90%
Go, Aubrey.

00:32:09.008 --> 00:32:09.508 align:middle line:90%
Go, Aubrey.

00:32:09.508 --> 00:32:12.410 align:middle line:90%
Go.

00:32:12.410 --> 00:32:14.210 align:middle line:84%
>>DE GREY: At this
point, we don't

00:32:14.210 --> 00:32:16.180 align:middle line:84%
know which of these
approaches is actually

00:32:16.180 --> 00:32:18.340 align:middle line:84%
going to be more
promising in the long run.

00:32:18.340 --> 00:32:20.950 align:middle line:84%
>>ANDREWS: And if it turns out
that telomerase is a bad thing,

00:32:20.950 --> 00:32:23.230 align:middle line:90%
that's really bad news for us.

00:32:23.230 --> 00:32:26.170 align:middle line:84%
Because there is no
way that we're ever

00:32:26.170 --> 00:32:29.640 align:middle line:84%
going to be able to cure aging
unless we can figure out a way

00:32:29.640 --> 00:32:31.690 align:middle line:84%
to prevent telomeres
from shortening.

00:32:31.690 --> 00:32:34.430 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: OK, so you chose to
focus on the stories of both

00:32:34.430 --> 00:32:37.410 align:middle line:84%
of these particular scientists,
very opposing stories.

00:32:37.410 --> 00:32:41.260 align:middle line:84%
Bill, who found finally
his lifelong love,

00:32:41.260 --> 00:32:45.370 align:middle line:84%
and who's a really
perfect match for him.

00:32:45.370 --> 00:32:48.700 align:middle line:84%
Throughout the course of the
film, they got married, right?

00:32:48.700 --> 00:32:51.210 align:middle line:84%
And you got to witness
that and be a part of that.

00:32:51.210 --> 00:32:54.870 align:middle line:84%
Did he know he was going to
marry her before the film?

00:32:54.870 --> 00:32:57.760 align:middle line:84%
Or were you a part of
that process as well?

00:32:57.760 --> 00:33:02.410 align:middle line:84%
>>SUSSBERG: Yeah, again, we like
to keep a very light footprint.

00:33:02.410 --> 00:33:04.710 align:middle line:84%
It's not like we told
Bill to get married.

00:33:04.710 --> 00:33:06.106 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:33:06.106 --> 00:33:06.605 align:middle line:90%
No pressure.

00:33:06.605 --> 00:33:07.604 align:middle line:90%
>>ALVARADO: No pressure.

00:33:07.604 --> 00:33:09.276 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Making a
documentary of my life.

00:33:09.276 --> 00:33:10.400 align:middle line:90%
No pressure to get married.

00:33:10.400 --> 00:33:11.140 align:middle line:90%
>>SUSSBERG: Yeah.

00:33:11.140 --> 00:33:13.560 align:middle line:84%
But we learned on
the first day that we

00:33:13.560 --> 00:33:16.850 align:middle line:84%
met him this story of how he was
engaged five different times.

00:33:16.850 --> 00:33:20.222 align:middle line:84%
He decided not to
become married.

00:33:20.222 --> 00:33:22.180 align:middle line:84%
And then he told us about
his girlfriend Molly,

00:33:22.180 --> 00:33:23.960 align:middle line:84%
who was amazing,
and how they planned

00:33:23.960 --> 00:33:25.210 align:middle line:90%
to go back to the Himalayas.

00:33:25.210 --> 00:33:26.510 align:middle line:90%
So that seed was planted.

00:33:26.510 --> 00:33:28.110 align:middle line:90%
I think he may have known.

00:33:28.110 --> 00:33:30.680 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, there
was an engagement.

00:33:30.680 --> 00:33:32.780 align:middle line:84%
But Bill could have
backed out of that.

00:33:32.780 --> 00:33:35.350 align:middle line:84%
But ultimately, we went back
to the Himalayas with him.

00:33:35.350 --> 00:33:38.920 align:middle line:84%
And sure enough, they were
planning this all along.

00:33:38.920 --> 00:33:41.790 align:middle line:84%
So we were vaguely aware
this was going to happen.

00:33:41.790 --> 00:33:44.020 align:middle line:84%
It was a two-person ceremony--
just the two of them,

00:33:44.020 --> 00:33:48.270 align:middle line:90%
and the monk Lama Sespel and us.

00:33:48.270 --> 00:33:50.516 align:middle line:84%
So we were witness
to their wedding.

00:33:50.516 --> 00:33:52.390 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So they got a
permanent wedding video

00:33:52.390 --> 00:33:53.961 align:middle line:84%
from you guys, which
is really nice.

00:33:53.961 --> 00:33:56.460 align:middle line:84%
>>ALVARADO: Literally, we put
together a video for them just

00:33:56.460 --> 00:33:57.032 align:middle line:90%
as a--

00:33:57.032 --> 00:33:57.740 align:middle line:90%
>>SUSSBERG: Yeah.

00:33:57.740 --> 00:34:00.670 align:middle line:84%
Actually, David was editing
on one of the off days

00:34:00.670 --> 00:34:02.750 align:middle line:84%
and gave it to them
as a wedding gift.

00:34:02.750 --> 00:34:03.900 align:middle line:90%
And they cherish it.

00:34:03.900 --> 00:34:04.930 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Very nice.

00:34:04.930 --> 00:34:06.834 align:middle line:84%
One of the listeners
at the screening

00:34:06.834 --> 00:34:08.250 align:middle line:84%
pointed out the
fact that they got

00:34:08.250 --> 00:34:10.986 align:middle line:84%
married in a temple that
believes in reincarnation.

00:34:10.986 --> 00:34:11.986 align:middle line:90%
>>ALVARADO: That's true.

00:34:11.986 --> 00:34:13.610 align:middle line:84%
And yet, they'd rather
not reincarnate.

00:34:13.610 --> 00:34:15.920 align:middle line:84%
They'd rather just
stay incarnate.

00:34:15.920 --> 00:34:17.750 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Just stay
living forever.

00:34:17.750 --> 00:34:20.830 align:middle line:84%
And now Aubrey, in his
several different situations,

00:34:20.830 --> 00:34:23.969 align:middle line:90%
his wife is a scientist.

00:34:23.969 --> 00:34:27.460 align:middle line:84%
And she was pretty
clearly not-- she

00:34:27.460 --> 00:34:32.040 align:middle line:84%
said this is not my scene to be
in a polyamorous relationship.

00:34:32.040 --> 00:34:34.900 align:middle line:84%
How do you really
display that information

00:34:34.900 --> 00:34:40.389 align:middle line:84%
without being partial
to her opinion on it?

00:34:40.389 --> 00:34:41.889 align:middle line:84%
>>SUSSBERG: Yeah,
that was something

00:34:41.889 --> 00:34:44.630 align:middle line:84%
that we certainly
wrestled with in the edit.

00:34:44.630 --> 00:34:47.837 align:middle line:84%
Ultimately, as
David said, the film

00:34:47.837 --> 00:34:50.170 align:middle line:84%
is a document of what we
learned over the course of four

00:34:50.170 --> 00:34:52.590 align:middle line:84%
years of pre-production,
production, and editing.

00:34:52.590 --> 00:34:56.270 align:middle line:84%
So it would be unfair to release
the film with Aubrey being

00:34:56.270 --> 00:34:58.350 align:middle line:84%
in this polyamorous
relationship without actually

00:34:58.350 --> 00:34:59.600 align:middle line:90%
hearing from Adelaide.

00:34:59.600 --> 00:35:02.550 align:middle line:84%
I think people want to know
what does his wife think.

00:35:02.550 --> 00:35:03.090 align:middle line:90%
So.

00:35:03.090 --> 00:35:05.810 align:middle line:84%
I think we did it in
a way that allowed

00:35:05.810 --> 00:35:08.110 align:middle line:90%
her to have a final word.

00:35:08.110 --> 00:35:12.120 align:middle line:84%
And Aubrey sees himself as
having a futuristic lifestyle.

00:35:12.120 --> 00:35:15.200 align:middle line:84%
Part of his futuristic lifestyle
involves many partners.

00:35:15.200 --> 00:35:17.150 align:middle line:90%
Adelaide didn't feel that way.

00:35:17.150 --> 00:35:20.630 align:middle line:84%
But ultimately, those were the
opinions of the characters.

00:35:20.630 --> 00:35:25.829 align:middle line:84%
And it wasn't really
our decision-making.

00:35:25.829 --> 00:35:27.370 align:middle line:84%
It was up to the
characters, and this

00:35:27.370 --> 00:35:28.578 align:middle line:90%
is the life they were living.

00:35:28.578 --> 00:35:31.829 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Right, and he said he's
the poster boy of anti-aging.

00:35:31.829 --> 00:35:32.870 align:middle line:90%
>>ALVARADO: That's right.

00:35:32.870 --> 00:35:36.090 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Is he as sarcastic
as he appears in the film?

00:35:36.090 --> 00:35:37.590 align:middle line:84%
>>ALVARADO: Oh,
yeah, absolutely.

00:35:37.590 --> 00:35:39.840 align:middle line:84%
Just trying to sit down with
him and get an interview,

00:35:39.840 --> 00:35:43.070 align:middle line:84%
questions answered, was
just-- it was funny at times,

00:35:43.070 --> 00:35:44.430 align:middle line:90%
frustrating at other times.

00:35:44.430 --> 00:35:48.100 align:middle line:84%
But ultimately, we really
enjoyed him as a person.

00:35:48.100 --> 00:35:53.220 align:middle line:84%
He's fun, and smart, and just
incredibly engaging to talk to.

00:35:53.220 --> 00:35:54.470 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Has he seen the film?

00:35:54.470 --> 00:35:55.100 align:middle line:84%
>>ALVARADO: He
has seen the film.

00:35:55.100 --> 00:35:55.600 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:35:55.600 --> 00:35:57.740 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And has he
commented back to you guys?

00:35:57.740 --> 00:35:58.620 align:middle line:90%
Or has he moved on?

00:35:58.620 --> 00:35:58.870 align:middle line:90%
>>ALVARADO: Yes.

00:35:58.870 --> 00:35:59.630 align:middle line:90%
He likes the film.

00:35:59.630 --> 00:36:01.210 align:middle line:90%
He hates the title.

00:36:01.210 --> 00:36:03.630 align:middle line:84%
For him, actually, the
title "The Immortalists"

00:36:03.630 --> 00:36:05.420 align:middle line:84%
is a little bit of a
mischaracterization

00:36:05.420 --> 00:36:06.620 align:middle line:90%
of what he's trying to do.

00:36:06.620 --> 00:36:08.140 align:middle line:84%
Because after all,
he's not trying

00:36:08.140 --> 00:36:10.080 align:middle line:90%
to make anybody immortal.

00:36:10.080 --> 00:36:13.980 align:middle line:84%
And so he knows why
we made that decision,

00:36:13.980 --> 00:36:17.362 align:middle line:84%
but ultimately, I
think he'll benefit.

00:36:17.362 --> 00:36:18.820 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I've said
several times, it

00:36:18.820 --> 00:36:23.410 align:middle line:84%
seems like a superhero complex,
that term "the immortalists."

00:36:23.410 --> 00:36:25.090 align:middle line:90%
We are here to save the day.

00:36:25.090 --> 00:36:28.710 align:middle line:84%
And that's not what
they're necessarily up to.

00:36:28.710 --> 00:36:30.680 align:middle line:84%
They're really up to
trying to sustain life

00:36:30.680 --> 00:36:34.040 align:middle line:84%
in a healthy way, which
is more important.

00:36:34.040 --> 00:36:36.420 align:middle line:84%
Do you have a plan for
a second documentary?

00:36:36.420 --> 00:36:38.590 align:middle line:84%
Has this sparked a
lot more conversations

00:36:38.590 --> 00:36:40.192 align:middle line:84%
as to where you want
to go from here?

00:36:40.192 --> 00:36:40.900 align:middle line:90%
>>SUSSBERG: Yeah.

00:36:40.900 --> 00:36:43.180 align:middle line:84%
David and I are
committed to doing films

00:36:43.180 --> 00:36:45.950 align:middle line:84%
on science, and
technology, and big ideas.

00:36:45.950 --> 00:36:49.625 align:middle line:84%
And so after this film, we
are doing pre-production

00:36:49.625 --> 00:36:53.530 align:middle line:84%
and research right now on a
couple of different topics.

00:36:53.530 --> 00:36:55.990 align:middle line:84%
So this isn't the
last film of ours.

00:36:55.990 --> 00:36:58.500 align:middle line:84%
We'll definitely keep on
producing stuff in the future.

00:36:58.500 --> 00:37:00.333 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And what were
you doing before this?

00:37:00.333 --> 00:37:02.750 align:middle line:90%
Before this particular film?

00:37:02.750 --> 00:37:06.660 align:middle line:84%
>>ALVARADO: We were in
graduate school together.

00:37:06.660 --> 00:37:08.620 align:middle line:84%
So we did a two-year
Master's of Fine Arts

00:37:08.620 --> 00:37:10.690 align:middle line:90%
program at Stanford University.

00:37:10.690 --> 00:37:13.960 align:middle line:90%
And we did a lot of short films.

00:37:13.960 --> 00:37:16.290 align:middle line:84%
10-minute films about
science and other things.

00:37:16.290 --> 00:37:19.640 align:middle line:84%
Jason did a political film
and a short film about science

00:37:19.640 --> 00:37:20.510 align:middle line:90%
as well.

00:37:20.510 --> 00:37:23.690 align:middle line:84%
And through watching each
other do our own films,

00:37:23.690 --> 00:37:26.780 align:middle line:84%
we saw that we're interested
in the same ideas.

00:37:26.780 --> 00:37:28.880 align:middle line:84%
And so sure enough,
we got together

00:37:28.880 --> 00:37:30.512 align:middle line:84%
to make this film
once we graduated.

00:37:30.512 --> 00:37:32.720 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Wow, so this is
fresh out of graduate school.

00:37:32.720 --> 00:37:33.180 align:middle line:90%
>>ALVARADO: That's right.

00:37:33.180 --> 00:37:34.930 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You've aired
it at film festivals,

00:37:34.930 --> 00:37:37.850 align:middle line:84%
and it's received a lot of
accolade from film festivals.

00:37:37.850 --> 00:37:39.010 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:37:39.010 --> 00:37:40.840 align:middle line:84%
>>SUSSBERG: Yeah,
we went all over.

00:37:40.840 --> 00:37:45.650 align:middle line:84%
The film's been in, I think,
over 30 to 40-ish festivals

00:37:45.650 --> 00:37:49.510 align:middle line:90%
all across America, the world.

00:37:49.510 --> 00:37:55.520 align:middle line:84%
We've played in Moscow,
Ireland, the UK, Copenhagen,

00:37:55.520 --> 00:37:56.050 align:middle line:90%
you name it.

00:37:56.050 --> 00:37:57.992 align:middle line:90%
It's really had an amazing run.

00:37:57.992 --> 00:37:59.950 align:middle line:84%
So we were really fortunate
and privileged too.

00:37:59.950 --> 00:38:02.050 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So across the
board, a great response.

00:38:02.050 --> 00:38:03.050 align:middle line:90%
>>ALVARADO: Pretty good.

00:38:03.050 --> 00:38:06.750 align:middle line:84%
There are critics who think
that we are either overly

00:38:06.750 --> 00:38:10.080 align:middle line:84%
enthusiastic about their
goals, and other critics

00:38:10.080 --> 00:38:12.637 align:middle line:84%
who think that we are
degrading their goals.

00:38:12.637 --> 00:38:14.470 align:middle line:84%
But we'd like to think
that we're leaving it

00:38:14.470 --> 00:38:16.700 align:middle line:84%
to the audience to
determine what they think

00:38:16.700 --> 00:38:19.380 align:middle line:84%
about these guys
and who they are.

00:38:19.380 --> 00:38:21.210 align:middle line:84%
But overall, we've
been very happy

00:38:21.210 --> 00:38:23.530 align:middle line:84%
with the critical review
of the film as a film.

00:38:23.530 --> 00:38:24.280 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:38:24.280 --> 00:38:26.760 align:middle line:84%
It's going to give you a
lot of attention as well.

00:38:26.760 --> 00:38:29.180 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to have you take a
look at this particular clip,

00:38:29.180 --> 00:38:31.140 align:middle line:84%
and again, you can
make your decision

00:38:31.140 --> 00:38:33.250 align:middle line:84%
about this story
that's depicted here.

00:38:33.250 --> 00:38:34.730 align:middle line:90%
Take a look.

00:38:34.730 --> 00:38:36.480 align:middle line:84%
>>ADELAIDE CARPENTER:
Aubrey's expectation

00:38:36.480 --> 00:38:40.910 align:middle line:84%
is for me to either
retire or have

00:38:40.910 --> 00:38:45.410 align:middle line:84%
some way of doing my
research in California.

00:38:45.410 --> 00:38:47.855 align:middle line:84%
And that just clearly
wouldn't work.

00:38:47.855 --> 00:38:52.810 align:middle line:90%


00:38:52.810 --> 00:38:54.910 align:middle line:84%
>>DE GREY: Certainly,
the expectation

00:38:54.910 --> 00:38:57.290 align:middle line:84%
of living a very long
time might very well

00:38:57.290 --> 00:39:03.325 align:middle line:84%
lead to a reevaluation of the
value of permanent monogamy.

00:39:03.325 --> 00:39:07.256 align:middle line:90%


00:39:07.256 --> 00:39:08.630 align:middle line:84%
>>CARPENTER: We're
still married.

00:39:08.630 --> 00:39:11.274 align:middle line:84%
We're still in love
with each other.

00:39:11.274 --> 00:39:12.690 align:middle line:84%
But he has to be
with other women.

00:39:12.690 --> 00:39:20.070 align:middle line:90%


00:39:20.070 --> 00:39:26.545 align:middle line:84%
His ideal, I think, would
be to have a situation where

00:39:26.545 --> 00:39:30.490 align:middle line:84%
all of his women lived
together, and he could just

00:39:30.490 --> 00:39:31.650 align:middle line:90%
live with all of them.

00:39:31.650 --> 00:39:36.470 align:middle line:84%
And I just so-- it's
so not my scene.

00:39:36.470 --> 00:39:41.020 align:middle line:90%


00:39:41.020 --> 00:39:44.060 align:middle line:84%
>>DE GREY: This is more or less
the beginning of the property.

00:39:44.060 --> 00:39:45.120 align:middle line:90%
That leads to the front.

00:39:45.120 --> 00:39:48.710 align:middle line:84%
There's another way up on my
left that goes to the back.

00:39:48.710 --> 00:39:52.692 align:middle line:84%
And then here's the
main thing up the drive.

00:39:52.692 --> 00:39:53.275 align:middle line:90%
Quite a sight.

00:39:53.275 --> 00:39:55.960 align:middle line:90%


00:39:55.960 --> 00:40:01.425 align:middle line:84%
I guess I can view myself as
something of a poster boy,

00:40:01.425 --> 00:40:05.255 align:middle line:84%
so to speak, for
future lifestyle.

00:40:05.255 --> 00:40:06.580 align:middle line:90%
So here's the amazing house.

00:40:06.580 --> 00:40:12.010 align:middle line:90%


00:40:12.010 --> 00:40:17.150 align:middle line:84%
I believe that in the
relatively near future when

00:40:17.150 --> 00:40:22.290 align:middle line:84%
we've brought aging under very
considerable medical control,

00:40:22.290 --> 00:40:24.960 align:middle line:84%
there's going to be much less
difference between people

00:40:24.960 --> 00:40:26.924 align:middle line:90%
of different chronological ages.

00:40:26.924 --> 00:40:30.410 align:middle line:90%


00:40:30.410 --> 00:40:33.226 align:middle line:84%
I have three
partners in my life,

00:40:33.226 --> 00:40:36.250 align:middle line:84%
and they are of
very different ages.

00:40:36.250 --> 00:40:40.640 align:middle line:84%
My wife is 68, and my two
girlfriends are 45 and 24.

00:40:40.640 --> 00:40:44.870 align:middle line:90%


00:40:44.870 --> 00:40:48.660 align:middle line:84%
>>KIM: We started a community
built as an immortality

00:40:48.660 --> 00:40:52.270 align:middle line:90%
and polyamorous haven.

00:40:52.270 --> 00:40:54.500 align:middle line:84%
And I feel lucky to
have found myself

00:40:54.500 --> 00:40:57.655 align:middle line:84%
in the melting pot
of these two realms.

00:40:57.655 --> 00:41:00.752 align:middle line:90%


00:41:00.752 --> 00:41:03.300 align:middle line:84%
>>DE GREY: What an
amazing place this is.

00:41:03.300 --> 00:41:07.489 align:middle line:84%
It's going to take me a while
to stop pinching myself.

00:41:07.489 --> 00:41:08.455 align:middle line:90%
Here we go.

00:41:08.455 --> 00:41:12.320 align:middle line:90%


00:41:12.320 --> 00:41:14.230 align:middle line:90%
Cheers, my love.

00:41:14.230 --> 00:41:18.290 align:middle line:84%
My ultimate goal on
the longevity mission

00:41:18.290 --> 00:41:20.530 align:middle line:90%
is to become obsolete.

00:41:20.530 --> 00:41:23.080 align:middle line:84%
To do enough that there
are people out there who

00:41:23.080 --> 00:41:26.430 align:middle line:84%
are better than me who,
therefore, will supplant me

00:41:26.430 --> 00:41:30.330 align:middle line:84%
in terms of being really the
spearhead of this mission.

00:41:30.330 --> 00:41:33.660 align:middle line:84%
And I will be very grateful
to have the opportunity

00:41:33.660 --> 00:41:36.150 align:middle line:84%
to retreat into
glorious obscurity.

00:41:36.150 --> 00:41:37.730 align:middle line:84%
And I can tell you
that this is where

00:41:37.730 --> 00:41:39.771 align:middle line:84%
I will be spending a lot
of that retreating time.

00:41:39.771 --> 00:41:42.460 align:middle line:90%


00:41:42.460 --> 00:41:44.070 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So the film
"The Immortalists"

00:41:44.070 --> 00:41:49.310 align:middle line:84%
has qualified for the Academy
Award in terms of documentary.

00:41:49.310 --> 00:41:52.600 align:middle line:84%
How does that work, for
future documentarians here?

00:41:52.600 --> 00:41:57.810 align:middle line:84%
How do you get a film to
qualify for the Academy's?

00:41:57.810 --> 00:41:59.980 align:middle line:84%
>>ALVARADO: So in order
to qualify for an Oscar,

00:41:59.980 --> 00:42:02.140 align:middle line:84%
you have to have a
certain theatrical run.

00:42:02.140 --> 00:42:03.990 align:middle line:84%
So that's playing
in New York City

00:42:03.990 --> 00:42:06.210 align:middle line:84%
for a week, a certain
amount of times,

00:42:06.210 --> 00:42:07.920 align:middle line:90%
a certain amount of days.

00:42:07.920 --> 00:42:12.172 align:middle line:84%
And then play in Los Angeles
for those same parameters.

00:42:12.172 --> 00:42:14.130 align:middle line:84%
And then you also have
to have a certain number

00:42:14.130 --> 00:42:16.620 align:middle line:84%
of critical reviews, so
from the "New York Times,"

00:42:16.620 --> 00:42:19.890 align:middle line:84%
and the "LA Times,"
"Village Voice."

00:42:19.890 --> 00:42:22.890 align:middle line:84%
All these people have reviewed
the film, mostly positively.

00:42:22.890 --> 00:42:25.830 align:middle line:84%
And from that certain
level of success,

00:42:25.830 --> 00:42:28.930 align:middle line:84%
we've qualified as a potential
for the future documentary

00:42:28.930 --> 00:42:29.637 align:middle line:90%
category.

00:42:29.637 --> 00:42:30.470 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting.

00:42:30.470 --> 00:42:32.909 align:middle line:84%
So it's pretty much
a clear cut thing

00:42:32.909 --> 00:42:34.950 align:middle line:84%
that you have to fit into
certain qualifications.

00:42:34.950 --> 00:42:35.410 align:middle line:90%
>>ALVARADO: That's right.

00:42:35.410 --> 00:42:37.670 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: How did you get the
distribution on the film?

00:42:37.670 --> 00:42:39.170 align:middle line:84%
How did you get
into these theaters?

00:42:39.170 --> 00:42:40.090 align:middle line:90%
How does that work?

00:42:40.090 --> 00:42:41.622 align:middle line:84%
As opposed to going
right to video.

00:42:41.622 --> 00:42:42.330 align:middle line:90%
>>ALVARADO: Sure.

00:42:42.330 --> 00:42:44.090 align:middle line:84%
Well, when we were
at film festivals,

00:42:44.090 --> 00:42:46.650 align:middle line:84%
we started to get approached
from different distributors who

00:42:46.650 --> 00:42:50.430 align:middle line:84%
wanted to distribute the film
theatrically and otherwise.

00:42:50.430 --> 00:42:52.220 align:middle line:84%
Gaiam TV actually
came along and was

00:42:52.220 --> 00:42:54.460 align:middle line:84%
very enthusiastic
about the film, thought

00:42:54.460 --> 00:42:56.710 align:middle line:84%
that it would be a successful
product for people who

00:42:56.710 --> 00:42:59.420 align:middle line:84%
were interested in health, and
longevity, and other things.

00:42:59.420 --> 00:43:01.150 align:middle line:84%
And so once we
talked to each other

00:43:01.150 --> 00:43:03.670 align:middle line:84%
and realized that this
would be a good partnership,

00:43:03.670 --> 00:43:04.290 align:middle line:90%
we signed off.

00:43:04.290 --> 00:43:06.680 align:middle line:90%
And now it's going really well.

00:43:06.680 --> 00:43:09.180 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And they're also helping
with the theatrical release

00:43:09.180 --> 00:43:11.385 align:middle line:84%
and getting it across the
country, and so forth?

00:43:11.385 --> 00:43:13.135 align:middle line:84%
>>ALVARADO: That's
right, through Gaiam TV

00:43:13.135 --> 00:43:14.970 align:middle line:84%
and another distributor
called Gathr,

00:43:14.970 --> 00:43:18.610 align:middle line:84%
which is a great distributor
for small filmmakers like Jason

00:43:18.610 --> 00:43:19.180 align:middle line:90%
and I.

00:43:19.180 --> 00:43:20.554 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yeah,
that's interesting.

00:43:20.554 --> 00:43:23.620 align:middle line:84%
So you can really create any
type of theatrical release

00:43:23.620 --> 00:43:24.620 align:middle line:90%
through these companies.

00:43:24.620 --> 00:43:27.750 align:middle line:84%
And they assist you to do that
to get the information out

00:43:27.750 --> 00:43:28.270 align:middle line:90%
there.

00:43:28.270 --> 00:43:30.920 align:middle line:84%
And then the Q&A's and
so forth afterwards,

00:43:30.920 --> 00:43:32.460 align:middle line:84%
do you always
encourage the audience

00:43:32.460 --> 00:43:35.607 align:middle line:84%
to stick around and ask
questions, and so forth?

00:43:35.607 --> 00:43:37.440 align:middle line:84%
>>SUSSBERG: Yeah, if
we're there, typically,

00:43:37.440 --> 00:43:40.920 align:middle line:84%
we'll always entertainment a Q&A
and have a lively discussion.

00:43:40.920 --> 00:43:44.032 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: What are the biggest
questions that you guys get?

00:43:44.032 --> 00:43:45.490 align:middle line:84%
>>ALVARADO: The
biggest questions--

00:43:45.490 --> 00:43:50.880 align:middle line:90%
it's always what about religion?

00:43:50.880 --> 00:43:52.890 align:middle line:90%
You didn't mention religion.

00:43:52.890 --> 00:43:55.234 align:middle line:84%
Or can you add more
science next time?

00:43:55.234 --> 00:43:56.400 align:middle line:90%
We're always happy to do it.

00:43:56.400 --> 00:43:57.941 align:middle line:84%
But then also, people
do want to know

00:43:57.941 --> 00:44:00.727 align:middle line:84%
if Jason and I are
willing to live longer.

00:44:00.727 --> 00:44:02.560 align:middle line:84%
If that would be something
that we would do.

00:44:02.560 --> 00:44:05.124 align:middle line:84%
And it's just so
fun to talk about.

00:44:05.124 --> 00:44:06.040 align:middle line:90%
So we really enjoy it.

00:44:06.040 --> 00:44:07.956 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And the average
age of the people that

00:44:07.956 --> 00:44:10.219 align:middle line:84%
come to see the movie,
are they older or younger?

00:44:10.219 --> 00:44:11.760 align:middle line:84%
>>ALVARADO: I'd say
across the board.

00:44:11.760 --> 00:44:12.690 align:middle line:90%
What would you say?

00:44:12.690 --> 00:44:14.356 align:middle line:84%
>>SUSSBERG: Yeah,
it's across the board.

00:44:14.356 --> 00:44:16.880 align:middle line:84%
I think it reflects folks
who go to film festivals.

00:44:16.880 --> 00:44:18.940 align:middle line:84%
And oftentimes,
they're students.

00:44:18.940 --> 00:44:20.640 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes, they're
young filmmakers

00:44:20.640 --> 00:44:22.390 align:middle line:90%
who want to watch a documentary.

00:44:22.390 --> 00:44:25.600 align:middle line:84%
Other times, they're
just an older baby boomer

00:44:25.600 --> 00:44:28.370 align:middle line:84%
crowd because that's the crowd
that goes to film festivals.

00:44:28.370 --> 00:44:30.190 align:middle line:90%
So it is across the board.

00:44:30.190 --> 00:44:32.420 align:middle line:84%
But I think it depends
on the flavor of the city

00:44:32.420 --> 00:44:34.870 align:middle line:84%
that we're playing and
what time we're playing.

00:44:34.870 --> 00:44:36.550 align:middle line:84%
11 o'clock in the
morning on Sunday

00:44:36.550 --> 00:44:38.180 align:middle line:84%
is going to be different
than 7 o'clock on Friday.

00:44:38.180 --> 00:44:38.560 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right, right.

00:44:38.560 --> 00:44:39.410 align:middle line:90%
Exactly.

00:44:39.410 --> 00:44:41.660 align:middle line:84%
OK, so are we going to
get an "Immortalists 2"?

00:44:41.660 --> 00:44:44.590 align:middle line:84%
Or is the new middle
age going to be 90?

00:44:44.590 --> 00:44:46.370 align:middle line:90%
Is that what's happening?

00:44:46.370 --> 00:44:47.453 align:middle line:90%
>>ALVARADO: You know what?

00:44:47.453 --> 00:44:50.352 align:middle line:84%
We'll check in with Aubrey and
Bill when they're 90 years old.

00:44:50.352 --> 00:44:52.060 align:middle line:84%
Maybe we'll consider
doing a sequel then.

00:44:52.060 --> 00:44:53.291 align:middle line:90%
>>SUSSBERG: 190.

00:44:53.291 --> 00:44:54.040 align:middle line:90%
Give it some time.

00:44:54.040 --> 00:44:54.623 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:44:54.623 --> 00:44:55.270 align:middle line:90%
190.

00:44:55.270 --> 00:44:57.780 align:middle line:90%
Living to 1,000 and beyond.

00:44:57.780 --> 00:44:59.050 align:middle line:90%
Well, thank you so much.

00:44:59.050 --> 00:45:01.770 align:middle line:84%
You've brought about a lot of
great points here in your film.

00:45:01.770 --> 00:45:06.210 align:middle line:84%
You did a great job of
explaining the story

00:45:06.210 --> 00:45:07.919 align:middle line:84%
in a beginning, middle,
and end of a film

00:45:07.919 --> 00:45:09.834 align:middle line:84%
so that we can make our
own decisions from it.

00:45:09.834 --> 00:45:12.130 align:middle line:84%
I think that's the quality
of a good documentary,

00:45:12.130 --> 00:45:14.560 align:middle line:84%
so that it actually
causes transformation

00:45:14.560 --> 00:45:16.820 align:middle line:84%
rather than doing the
transformation for you.

00:45:16.820 --> 00:45:20.750 align:middle line:84%
So it causes thought processes
and many different things.

00:45:20.750 --> 00:45:22.770 align:middle line:90%
So I appreciate you being here.

00:45:22.770 --> 00:45:24.750 align:middle line:84%
Thank you so much
for joining me today.

00:45:24.750 --> 00:45:24.970 align:middle line:90%
>>SUSSBERG: Thank you.

00:45:24.970 --> 00:45:25.220 align:middle line:90%
>>ALVARADO: Thanks.

00:45:25.220 --> 00:45:27.844 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And if you would like to
watch a replay of my interview

00:45:27.844 --> 00:45:30.170 align:middle line:84%
here with the filmmakers
of "The Immortalists,"

00:45:30.170 --> 00:45:32.710 align:middle line:90%
you can go to gaiamtv.com.

00:45:32.710 --> 00:45:36.350 align:middle line:84%
And until next time, I
invite you to stay inspired.

